Chellette Henderson and J. Terry Davis speak to Jordan Chariton about Selma, AL's voting rights legacy and their family history which they have traced back to ancestors who were slaves

LIVE from Selma, AL -- Survivors of "Bloody Sunday" reunite to commemorate the 52nd anniversary of the most infamous act of police brutality in American history. This afternoon, thousands will reenact the courageous bridge crossing that led to the passage of the Voting Rights Act. 

The Alabama government had ordered law enforcement and deputized white civilians to prevent African Americans and their allies from marching from Selma to Montgomery to demand the right to vote. News footage of the resulting acts of political violence shocked the nation and sparked a chain reaction that led to the passage of be 1965 Voting Rights Act five months later. The VRA protected the right to vote for minorities in America until the Shelby v. Holder Supreme Court decision of 2013, the most decisive blow in the conservative backlash against voting rights until the swearing in of Selma-born arch-conservative Jeff Sessions as U.S. Attorney General. 

Subscribe to YouTube.com/TYTpolitics
link_name: Selma, Alabama Bridge Crossing

University of Arizona- Tucson
presents 
The Young Turks on FUSION, Nov. 21, at 6 PM MT. 

The weekly, hour-long live election-focused show from TYT Network and FUSION – broadcasts LIVE from Crowder Hall at University of Arizona- Tucson, marking the show's final episode of a national 12-campus tour.

Hosts John Iadarola and Ana Kasparian of The Young Turks will be joined by FUSION's Ryan Nerz as well as special guest, comedian, Alonzo Bodden.

The episode, which will air on FUSION's cable channel and digital properties, will focus on post-election, especially discussing the first 100 days of the Trump presidency. 

The Young Turks on FUSION aims to discuss the most important issues facing young people this election season. From in-depth discussions on education reform and international terrorism, to man-on-the-street Q&As and game show segments, The Young Turks on FUSION is engaging college students and viewers nationwide leading up to the presidential election.

RSVP for your FREE tickets at the link below! Share with your friends!

Once you RSVP at the link, your name will be added to our attendee listing. Please RSVP for each guest attending with you. Then, on Nov 21, just check-in by last name outside the venue.

As this is a LIVE TV show broadcast, please arrive by 5 PM MT to check-in and be seated by 5:30 PM. 

Digital pre-show festivities begin promptly at 5:45 PM. Show begins promptly at 6 PM MT. 

Seats are first come, first get.

status_message:
Harvard Institute of Politics
presents 
The Young Turks on FUSION, Nov. 14, at 8 PM ET. 

The weekly, hour-long live election-focused show from TYT Network and FUSION broadcasts LIVE from JFK Jr. Forum at Harvard Institute of Politics, marking the show's eleventh episode of a national 12-campus tour.

Hosts Cenk Uygur and John Iadarola of The Young Turks will be joined by FUSION's Felix Salmon as well as special guests, Republican Strategist & HUIOP Fellow, Sarah Isgur Flores and Former Obama Aide & NY State Assembly member Michael Blake (D-79th District).

The episode, which will air on FUSION's cable channel and digital properties, will focus on post-election, especially discussing: Are Republicans happy? What will both political parties look like it the future? Trump foreign policy and Russian relations? Are moderate politics dead?

The Young Turks on FUSION aims to discuss the most important issues facing young people this election season. From in-depth discussions on education reform and international terrorism, to man-on-the-street Q&As and game show segments, The Young Turks on FUSION is engaging college students and viewers nationwide leading up to the presidential election.

RSVP for your FREE tickets at the link below! Share with your friends!

Once you RSVP at the link, your name will be added to our attendee listing. Please RSVP for each guest attending with you. Then, on Nov 14, just check-in by last name outside the Forum.

As this is a LIVE TV show broadcast, please arrive by 7 PM ET to check-in and be seated by 7:30 PM. 

Digital pre-show festivities begin promptly at 7:45 PM. Show begins promptly at 8 PM ET. 

Seats are first come, first get.

The Associated Students at the University of Nevada (ASUN)
presents 
The Young Turks on FUSION, Nov. 7, at 5 PM PT. 

The weekly, hour-long live election-focused show from TYT Network and FUSION – broadcasts LIVE from Milt Glick Ballroom (Ballroom A) at Joe Crowley Student Union at University of Nevada-Reno, marking the show's ninth episode of a national 12-campus tour.

Hosts Ana Kasparian and John Iadarola of The Young Turks will be joined by FUSION's Natasha Del Toro and a special guest.

The episode, which will air on FUSION's cable channel and digital properties, will focus on the presidential election, with specific conversation about new development on the Eve of the Election, as well as discussion on swing states. 

The Young Turks on FUSION aims to discuss the most important issues facing young people this election season. From in-depth discussions on education reform and international terrorism, to man-on-the-street Q&As and game show segments, The Young Turks on FUSION is engaging college students and viewers nationwide leading up to the presidential election.

RSVP for your FREE tickets at the link below! Share with your friends!

Once you RSVP at the link, your name will be added to our attendee listing. Please RSVP for each guest attending with you. Then, on Nov 7, just check-in by last name outside the ballroom. 

As this is a LIVE TV show broadcast, please arrive by 4 PM PT to check-in and be seated by 4:30 PM. 

Digital pre-show festivities begin promptly at 4:50 PM. Show begins promptly at 5 PM PT. 

Seats are first come, first get.

Loyola University
presents 
The Young Turks on FUSION, Oct. 31, at 7 PM CT. 

The weekly, hour-long live election-focused show from TYT Network and FUSION – broadcasts LIVE from Audubon Room at Danna Student Center, marking the show's eighth episode in a national 12-campus tour.

Hosts Ana Kasparian and John Iadarola of The Young Turks will be joined by FUSION's Dodai Stewart and special guest, comedian, Chris Cubas! 

The episode, which will air on FUSION's cable channel and digital properties, will focus on the presidential election.

The Young Turks on FUSION aims to discuss the most important issues facing young people this election season. From in-depth discussions on education reform and international terrorism, to man-on-the-street Q&As and game show segments, The Young Turks on FUSION is engaging college students and viewers nationwide leading up to the presidential election.

RSVP for your FREE tickets at the link below! Share with your friends!

Once you RSVP at the link, your name will be added to our attendee listing. Please RSVP for each guest attending with you. Then, on Oct 31, just check-in by last name the evening of the event outside the event room. 

As this is a LIVE TV show broadcast, please arrive by 6 PM to check-in and be seated by 6:30 PM. 

Digital pre-show festivities begin promptly at 6:30 PM. Show begins promptly at 7 PM ET.

The Men's Glee Club at the University of Michigan 
presents 
The Young Turks on FUSION, Oct. 3, at 8 PM ET. 

The weekly, hour-long live election-focused show from TYT Network and FUSION  – broadcasts LIVE from Rogel Ballroom on the campus of the University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, marking the show's fourth episode in a national 12-campus tour.

Hosts Cenk Uygur and John Iadarola of The Young Turks will be joined by FUSION anchor Alicia Menendez and Flint activist, Laura MacIntyre.

The episode, which will air on FUSION's cable channel and digital properties, will focus on the presidential election.

The Young Turks on FUSION aims to discuss the most important issues facing young people this election season. From in-depth discussions on education reform and international terrorism, to man-on-the-street Q&As and game show segments, The Young Turks on FUSION is engaging college students and viewers nationwide leading up to the presidential election.

RSVP for your FREE tickets at the link below! Share with your friends!

Once you RSVP at the link, your name will be added to our attendee listing. Please check-in by last name the evening of the event outside the ballroom. 

As this is a LIVE TV show broadcast, please arrive by 7 PM to check-in and be seated by 7:30 PM. 

Digital pre-show festivities begin promptly at 7:30 PM. Show begins promptly at 8 PM ET.

status_message:
TYT's Eric Byler interviews Transgender Equality Activist Erica Lachowitz at the Wake County Detention Center in Raleigh, NC where people arrested for protesting HB2 will soon be released. 

HB2 is also known as the "bathroom" bill because it prevents local governments from protecting the rights of transgender Americans to use the public restroom of their choice. But it also takes away the rights of local governments to increase the minimum wage and encourage women and minority hiring, and it prevents legal action for those who suffer workplace discrimination.

Civil Rights leader Rev. Dr. William Barber II has asked participants not to respond to counter-protesters in support of the new law requiring proof that a person use the bathroom that corresponds to the gender of their birth. He has also said, "Please don't call House Bill 2 'The Bathroom Bill.' because if you read Section 2 and Section 3, it also takes away the right of municipalities to increase the minimum wage. NC Republicans need the "bathroom" hysteria headlines to cover up this attack on the Fight for 15, because their actions would be deeply unpopular with voters if they did this straight up. 80% of North Carolinians support increasing the minimum wage. 

North Carolina Republicans are stoking bigotry, he asserts, and using the trans-gender community to disguise a cynical attack on labor, women, and families on behalf of business interests, and, to rally the base of the Republican party for November's crucial election.

There are historical comparisons in which African Americans have been scapegoated and used in this way, including the wave of terrorism that overturned democratically elected biracial governments in the South in the decades following the Civil War, and the hateful electioneering of former NC Senator Jesse Helms. Thus, the the multi-faith and multi-racial Moral Movement is organizing a mass sit-in on Monday to expose the hidden agenda behind the so-called Bathroom Bill.

Instead of The Bathroom Bill, call it The Anti worker, Anti-Living wage, Anti-Family, Anti-Women, Anti-Civil Rights, Anti-Gay, Anti-Transgender Bill.

GOP lawmakers hoped we'd focus on the bathroom controversy, and not read Sec 2 and Sec. 3 which prohibit city governments such as Charlotte's and Greensboro's from requiring contractors to pay a living wage and afford workers with vacation sick leave. 

It also takes away the ability to file employment discrimination suits in in state court.

Too many in the news media fall for the sensationalism of the Ted Cruz argument that little girls will fall prey to sexual predators if their entry to girls' bathrooms is not prohibited by state law. 

The Orwellian moniker, "Religious Freedom" reminds historians of previous dishonest, hate-based movements cloaked in false religiosity. 

The 14th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution guaranteed for the first time that people who had been legally codified as three-fifths persons would enjoy equal protection under the law in this country. But the very notion of equal protection under law for African Americans was so offensive that it inspired a violent, orchestrated backlash, led by terrorist organizations such as the KKK working in concert with former slave owner/aristocrat/politicians.
link_name: Interview with Transgender Equality Activist Erica Lachowitz

Is North Carolina's "Bathroom" Law a Political Ploy for November, or a Sneak Attack on the Living Wage?

"It doesn't matter that it's unconstitutional," said Josh Stein, currently leading the race to become North Carolina's next Attorney General. "We cannot afford self-inflicted wounds where we are putting ourself at a competitive disadvantage. There have been thousands of lost jobs as a result of this bill, tens of millions of dollars of foregone investment that could have strengthened our economy here, and the damage to our brand is incalculable."

Concerned that North Carolina's "Bathroom Bill" — a knee-jerk reaction to the city of Charlotte passing a law to protect the rights of transgender residents — is hurting the states ability to compete with neighboring states to attract businesses and investment, Stein told TYT's Eric Byler, "As of last week, there have been 50 thousand media hits with 18 billion impressions, that's 3 impressions for every person on this planet.

Josh Stein spoke to us by phone from Durham, NC, a city for which served for 8 years in the North Carolina state senate. There Stein was an outspoken leader in the fight to expand voting rights and offer protections against discrimination, and, after those measures had proven successful, against a radical, and legally dubious backlash that included historic voting restrictions & infringements upon reproductive rights. 

Stein's opponent for Attorney General, state senator Buck Newton, is one of the main champions of the "Bathroom Bill," and also supported the voting restrictions & abortion restrictions that passed in 2013. Stein left the NC state senate in March after winning the North Carolina primary race for Attorney General.

Department of Justice takes historic stand to protect the rights of transgender community. TYT's Eric Byler with a brief analysis.  

NOTE: On Monday, May 16, 2016, North Carolinians will again occupy the General Assembly building at 4 pm. (3 pm for those planning to risk arrest). Eric Byler will be there to stream live via Facebook Live. MORE INFO: https://www.facebook.com/events/470197463175635/

Statement by U.S. Attorney General Loretta Lynch:

The North Carolina General Assembly passed House Bill 2 in special session on March 23 of this year. The bill sought to strike down an anti-discrimination provision in a recently-passed Charlotte, North Carolina, ordinance, as well as to require transgender people in public agencies to use the bathrooms consistent with their sex as noted at birth, rather than the bathrooms that fit their gender identity. The bill was signed into law that same day. In so doing, the legislature and the governor placed North Carolina in direct opposition to federal laws prohibiting discrimination on the basis of sex and gender identity. More to the point, they created state-sponsored discrimination against transgender individuals, who simply seek to engage in the most private of functions in a place of safety and security – a right taken for granted by most of us.

Last week, our Civil Rights Division notified state officials that House Bill 2 violates federal civil rights laws. We asked that they certify by the end of the day today that they would not comply with or implement House Bill 2's restriction on restroom access. An extension was requested by North Carolina and was under active consideration. But instead of replying to our offer or providing a certification, this morning, the state of North Carolina and its governor chose to respond by suing the Department of Justice. As a result of their decisions, we are now moving forward.

Today, we are filing a federal civil rights lawsuit against the state of North Carolina, Governor Pat McCrory, the North Carolina Department of Public Safety and the University of North Carolina. We are seeking a court order declaring House Bill 2's restroom restriction impermissibly discriminatory, as well as a statewide bar on its enforcement. While the lawsuit currently seeks declaratory relief, I want to note that we retain the option of curtailing federal funding to the North Carolina Department of Public Safety and the University of North Carolina as this case proceeds.

This action is about a great deal more than just bathrooms. This is about the dignity and respect we accord our fellow citizens and the laws that we, as a people and as a country, have enacted to protect them – indeed, to protect all of us. And it's about the founding ideals that have led this country – haltingly but inexorably – in the direction of fairness, inclusion and equality for all Americans.

This is not the first time that we have seen discriminatory responses to historic moments of progress for our nation. We saw it in the Jim Crow laws that followed the Emancipation Proclamation. We saw it in fierce and widespread resistance to Brown v. Board of Education. And we saw it in the proliferation of state bans on same-sex unions intended to stifle any hope that gay and lesbian Americans might one day be afforded the right to marry. That right, of course, is now recognized as a guarantee embedded in our Constitution, and in the wake of that historic triumph, we have seen bill after bill in state after state taking aim at the LGBT community. Some of these responses reflect a recognizably human fear of the unknown, and a discomfort with the uncertainty of change. But this is not a time to act out of fear. This is a time to summon our national virtues of inclusivity, diversity, compassion and open-mindedness. What we must not do – what we must never do – is turn on our neighbors, our family members, our fellow Americans, for something they cannot control, and deny what makes them human. This is why none of us can stand by when a state enters the business of legislating identity and insists that a person pretend to be something they are not, or invents a problem that doesn't exist as a pretext for discrimination and harassment.

Let me speak now to the people of the great state, the beautiful state, my state of North Carolina. You've been told that this law protects vulnerable populations from harm – but that just is not the case. Instead, what this law does is inflict further indignity on a population that has already suffered far more than its fair share. This law provides no benefit to society – all it does is harm innocent Americans.

Instead of turning away from our neighbors, our friends, our colleagues, let us instead learn from our history and avoid repeating the mistakes of our past. Let us reflect on the obvious but often neglected lesson that state-sanctioned discrimination never looks good in hindsight. It was not so very long ago that states, including North Carolina, had signs above restrooms, water fountains and on public accommodations keeping people out based upon a distinction without a difference. We have moved beyond those dark days, but not without pain and suffering and an ongoing fight to keep moving forward. Let us write a different story this time. Let us not act out of fear and misunderstanding, but out of the values of inclusion, diversity and regard for all that make our country great.

Let me also speak directly to the transgender community itself. Some of you have lived freely for decades. Others of you are still wondering how you can possibly live the lives you were born to lead. But no matter how isolated or scared you may feel today, the Department of Justice and the entire Obama Administration wants you to know that we see you; we stand with you; and we will do everything we can to protect you going forward. Please know that history is on your side. This country was founded on a promise of equal rights for all, and we have always managed to move closer to that promise, little by little, one day at a time. It may not be easy – but we'll get there together.

I want to thank my colleagues in the Civil Rights Division who have devoted many hours to this case so far, and who will devote many more to seeing it through.

status_message:
Pt. 9  LBGTQ Youth Rock the General Assembly Responsible for "Hate Bill 2"

NOTE: Sound starts late in this segment. 

LIVE from Raleigh, NC state capitol: protesters planning mass sit-in to protest #HateBill2 a.k.a. the Bathroom Bill.  Eric Byler reporting for The Young Turks. 

Civil Rights leader Rev. Dr. William Barber II has asked participants not to respond to counter-protesters in support of the new law requiring proof that a person use the bathroom that corresponds to the gender of their birth.  He has also said, "Please don't call House Bill 2 'The Bathroom Bill.' because if you read Section 2 and Section 3, it also takes away the right of municipalities to increase the minimum wage.  NC Republicans need the "bathroom" hysteria headlines to cover up this attack on the Fight for 15, because their actions would be deeply unpopular with voters if they did this straight up.   80% of North Carolinians support increasing the minimum wage.  

North Carolina Republicans are stoking bigotry, he asserts, and using the trans-gender community to disguise a cynical attack on labor, women, and families on behalf of business interests, and, to rally the base of the Republican party for November's crucial election.

There are historical comparisons in which African Americans have been scapegoated and used in this way, including the wave of terrorism that overturned democratically elected biracial governments in the South in the decades following the Civil War, and the hateful electioneering of former NC Senator Jesse Helms.  Thus, the the multi-faith and multi-racial Moral Movement is organizing a mass sit-in on Monday to expose the hidden agenda behind the so-called Bathroom Bill.

Instead of The Bathroom Bill, call it The Anti worker, Anti-Living wage, Anti-Family, Anti-Women, Anti-Civil Rights, Anti-Gay, Anti-Transgender Bill.

GOP lawmakers hoped we'd focus on the bathroom controversy, and not read Sec 2 and Sec. 3 which prohibit city governments such as Charlotte's and Greensboro's from requiring contractors to pay a living wage and afford workers with vacation sick leave. 

It also takes away the ability to file employment discrimination suits in in state court.

Too many in the news media fall for the sensationalism of the Ted Cruz argument that little girls will fall prey to sexual predators if their entry to girls' bathrooms is not prohibited by state law. 

The Orwellian moniker, "Religious Freedom" reminds historians of previous dishonest, hate-based movements cloaked in false religiosity.   

The 14th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution guaranteed for the first time that people who had been legally codified as three-fifths persons would enjoy equal protection under the law in this country. But the very notion of equal protection under law for African Americans was so offensive that it inspired a violent, orchestrated backlash, led by terrorist organizations such as the KKK working in concert with former slave owner/aristocrat/politicians.
link_name: Pt. 9: LBGTQ Youth Rock the General Assembly Responsible for "...

The 14th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution guaranteed for the first time that people who had been legally codified as three-fifths persons would enjoy equal protection under the law in this country. But the very notion of equal protection under law for African Americans was so offensive that it inspired a violent, orchestrated backlash, led by terrorist organizations such as the KKK working in concert with former slave owner/aristocrat/politicians.

status_message:
Merrick Garland, President Obama's nominee to the Supreme Court is super conservative. This is ridiculous. He voted to allow unlimited contributions to PACs in SpeechNow. Apologists will claim that he had to vote that way because of Citizens United precedent, but the FEC made a perfectly reasonable counter-point to limit contributions -- and he rejected it. He is for more money in politics!

He also voted against fundamental human rights in Al Odah v. United States.

Reason.com, which I believe is a libertarian site, explains his vote this way:

"Garland voted in support of the George W. Bush administration's controversial war on terrorism policies in the Guantanamo detainee case Al Odah v. United States, in which Garland joined the majority opinion holding that enemy combatants held as detainees at the U.S. military facility at Guantanamo Bay were not entitled to habeus corpus protections. The U.S. Supreme Court ultimately overruled that decision, holding in the landmark case Boumediene v. Bush that Guantanamo detainees do enjoy habeus corpus rights."

So, let's get this right -- he is more conservative than the unbelieveably conservative current Supreme Court. Voting against habeus corpus is pro-Dick Cheney and anti-Magna Carta.

And this is not some sort of political trick by Obama. He really likes this guy, he had him on a short list back in 2010 when Stevens was being replaced. So, there goes the best argument to vote for Democrats -- they'll put progressives on the Supreme Court. Apparently not.

link_name: Secular Talk Radio - The Kyle Kulinski Show

status_message:
Bernie won Super Tuesday! Let me explain why.

Going into tonight it was unclear what was going to happen because the polling was so shoddy in some states, especially Colorado and Minnesota. Those two states are so important because of what they mean for the future. 

It turns out that Hillary Clinton won all of the states she was supposed to win -- and a narrow victory in Massachusetts (remember she won Mass. by 16 points against Obama and still lost the primary in 2008). But Bernie Sanders had resounding wins in CO & MN. Those two states are much more indicative of the states that are coming in the rest of the primary schedule.

All of these Southern states were Hillary Clinton's best states (by the way, also irrelevant places to have strength in for the general election). She's used up most of her ammo and doesn't even know what kind of trouble she's in. Right before the voting, she pivoted toward the right again in anticipation of the general election. Big mistake. She can't help herself; she lives and breaths arrogance.

Tonight could have been the knock out punch if HC had won CO & MN. But she didn't! She lost them big. Now, he has a $40 million war chest and favorable map in front of him. Feel the Bern!

Time is on Bernie's side. The more he runs, the more people find out about him. Everyone already knows Clinton. She's gaining no new voters. Every day he gains ground. So, now he lives to fight many other days. She is in a race against time and she didn't close the door tonight. Tick, tock. Tick, tock!

March 8th is huge because whoever wins Michigan has momentum going into March 15th - the real Super Tuesday (FL, OH, IL, NC and MO). That's Colossal Tuesday. And maybe the Ides of March for Hillary Clinton. 

Watch all of TYT's coverage of Super Tuesday here:

https://www.youtube.com/user/TheYoungTurks/videos

The Bernie Sanders campaign rolled into Ft. Collins, CO just one day after a resounding loss to Hillary Clinton in South Carolina.  Over 6,000 people filled the basketball arena at Colorado State University in Ft. Collins, CO, where Bernie Sanders dialed up his rhetoric in challenging the former Secretary of State on her ties to Wall Street, her vote to authorize the Iraq War, and her campaign's argument that incremental change that is likely is more practical than radical change that is difficult to achieve.   

TYT reporter Jordan Chariton asked Sanders supporters if they felt deflated after the South Carolina loss, and, whether or not they'd vote for Clinton if she is the Democratic nominee.

status_message:
The Young Turks January 4, 2016 Hour 2 

Ana and Iadarola hosting. A photographer posted a picture of the aftermath of a New Year's party where drunk partiers were passed out in the street. Social media took the image and compared it to Renaissance art. A meat packing plant with goals of producing tons of meat per day are having issues with Muslim employees needing to pray 5x per day. Some workers protested and eventually got fired for missing work. A new dating website called Where White People Meet is causing an uproar.

A person that isn't affiliated with a specific gender is crowdfunding for breast reduction surgery. Ana breaks down the tough situation the individual is in. An Instagram star has garnered attention for posting videos of smashing bread on her face. John gets mad about the success people have on Instagram. A Florida police dept is under investigation for laundering tons of money for drug cartels.
link_name: The Young Turks January 4, 2016 Hour 2

status_message:
The Young Turks January 4, 2016 Hour 1 

Cenk hosting. Carly Fiorina over the weekend released a pander Tweet on the Iowa vs Stanford game along with a video of her appearing on CNN saying "Can't a girl have a little fun". The Associated Press reports that emails have been released between the Chicago Police Department and the mayor's office over the murder of Laquan McDonald, with Rahm Emanuel already having knowledge of the murder along with concerns of a potential public relations disaster.

Armed right-wing militiamen have taken over a federal wildlife refuge headquarters in rural Oregon and vowed to remain in place. The occupation began after a protest Saturday in support of two ranchers sentenced to prison for setting fires that burned federal land. Video of Ammon Bundy the son of Cliven Bundy voiced his support saying "it's not a time to stand down, it's a time to stand up" along with appearing on CNN mentioning that there is no threat of violence and the threat of violence is coming from the federal government.  Cenk makes some observations from the mainstream press coverage between the Oregon Bureau Of Land Management takeover and Black Lives Matter.  

In response to the takeover of the federal building in Oregon by the Bundy ranchers, social media responded with hashtags that mocked how these hicks are an American version of Muslim terrorists. Saudi Arabia and Iran are in the middle of a heated battle after a Shiite clergyman was beheaded by the Saudi government. Harsh words have been spoken by both leaders, leading to Iranian protesters to converge on the Saudi embassy in Tehran, setting fire to much of the building. The Saudi foreign minister announced that they are severing all ties with Iran, while kicking Iranians out of their embassy in Saudi Arabia, and calling for their officials in Iran to come home immediately. Ben Carson and Carly Fiorina came out in blind support for the Saudis regarding their part in the violence.
link_name: The Young Turks January 4, 2016 Hour 1

status_message:
The Young Turks June 29, 2015 Hour 2

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLTpcK80irdQhTA_cLSLVtMgX77Z8ru1wp

A previous viral video of a Russian waitress fighting back against a patron for making a lewd advance has been revealed as a hoax and as for the restaurant, according to France 24. Texas Attorney General Ken Paxton is the latest Republican for his disapproval of the Supreme Court's decision on gay marriages, by giving clerk's a pass for not issuing marriage licences, for religious reasons. Mike Huckabee has released statements on the decision and makes an attempt to follow the path of Martin Luther King, to fight against the Supreme Court's decision. Rep Andy Gibson of Mississippi also despises the decision and feels that Mississippi should get out of the business of issuing marriage licences. Pat Robinson chimes in with his views saying there will be a love of anal sex. Cenk mentions a study from LiveScience, on the internal and external reactions of homophobes towards the LGBT community and the study reveals the true internal nature of homophobes. Donald Trump appears on CNN and discusses his three marriages and his observations on same sex marriages. NBC will no longer air "Miss Universe", "Miss USA" & "The Apprentice" with Donald Trump along with ending their business relationship with Trump, because of his derogatory statements toward illegal immigrants.

Bristol Palin has revealed that getting pregnant for the second time is planned and says that "it's not a mistake according to the giddy assholes". A shocking video has surfaced of a Philadelphia cop assaulting and arresting a man, for not paying the train fare, with his young daughter watching the incident. Rihanna duct tapes Floyd Mayweather's mouth shut at a BET awards ceremony, in an attempt of making a joke that goes wrong. Southern Poverty Law Center reports that six black churches last week, have been the victim of arson, in the reaction from the Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church shooting.
link_name: The Young Turks June 29, 2015 Hour 2

status_message:
The Young Turks June 29, 2015 Hour 1

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLTpcK80irdQhQyVZ2cJLWGSmNqmihXRnD

Cenk hosting. Senator Jim Inhofe of Oklahoma despises the recent Supreme Court decision on gay marriage, saying that his friends in the gay community were disappointed with the decision. Bobby Jindal recently announced his candidacy for president making him number 16 in the field and has revealed his logo for his campaign "Tanned, Rested, Ready to Go". CNN reports on spotting an ISIS flag at a gay pride parade in London, Cenk reveals the true design of the flag, along with Lucy Pawle from CNN being totally unaware of the flag design. In Istanbul Turkey a gay pride was disrupted in Taksim Square by police with water cannons, the motives for the disruption is unclear, but a beautiful rainbow was created by the water cannons.

Bree Newsome of South Carolina couragely climbed up a flagpole to remove a Confederate flag, with police officers watching and arresting her, along with Jameson Tyson for the act of civil disobedience. A planned counter protest showed up later for the Confederate flag. Greece's financial troubles are escalating, with its debt reaching at 1.77 billion dollars, Reuters reports on the situation, with Greece's banks closing till July 5th and its ATM's will only withdraw 60 Euros a day in order to avoid a total economic collapse. 38 British tourists were killed from an attack in Tunisia, with some staff members of a hotel, using themselves as human shields, on a beach, to protect others from harm's way.

Chris Hayes of MSNBC breaks down and apologizes to Bill O'Reilly for misquoting Bill on a discussion of the Confederate flag with Juan Williams of NPR, Cenk shows a release of another apology and talks about the management of MSNBC. The Supreme Court decision, on limiting regulations of power plants, with an opinion by Judge Alito showing his love for corporations.
link_name: The Young Turks June 29, 2015 Hour 1
